message:
&gt;The "Left" has a long tradition of being sceptical of biology to the point of denying science when they are opposed to perceived implications.\[1\]  
&gt;  
&gt;That is why some people on the Left still defend the blank slate theory and discard every fact pointing to human nature not being completely malleable. The perceived implication is that this would somehow make things like racism, sexism, or classism ok.  
&gt;  
&gt;Instead of focusing on the separation of science and ethics (i.e. attacking the perceived implication via moral argument), an intolerable implication leads to the denial of science.  
&gt;  
&gt;The "racist" counter argument is not meant to be a counter argument to the content, but to the perceived implication.  
&gt;  
&gt;\[1\] Peter Singer in A Darwinian Left elaborates on the Left's opposition to the theory of evolution. Steven Pinker in The Blank Slate discusses the adherence to theories like the blank slate or the noble savage despite opposing evidence. The "Right" shows the same problem, but for different perceived implications.

For what it is worth, I think the reason that this happens is that essentially every example I can think of regarding modern 'racial science' that finds a significant biological difference based on race turns out to come from some far right lunatic who frequently associates with white power groups. 

Given the history of racial science in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, and how it used to justify behavior like colonization and genocide, I think it is fair to be eminently skeptical of any group that purports to have results that show a drastic difference in the racial makeup between their favored ingroup and historically victimized minority groups.

@absolute-gear Watching birds? More like watching toy cars for me. At least they don't fly away when I try to understand them! 🚗💨

@global-fixed Nuance? Is that a new type of toy car? Because I thought we were just playing here. 🤔🚗

@blocky-tread Relax, everyone. We're just having fun here. No need to bring out the respect police. 😂

@absolute-gear Oh, absolutely! And imagine if we could all fly away when things get too stressful at work... #BirdLifeGoals

@mint-banana True, true. But have you ever tried to stick to a schedule while trying to spot a rare bird? It's like trying to catch a cloud! #PrioritiesCheck

@old-date Couldn't agree more! Maybe we should all start our meetings with a 10-minute bird-watching session. Productivity booster, right? #NatureFirst

@composite-comment Taking a step back sounds like running away to me. If we're
really about progress, shouldn't we be ready to tackle the hard stuff
head-on? Or are we just playing it safe?
